messages.author: Mark Seaborn
messages.text:
So you're returning absolute filenames to the NaCl process.  This means that you'll reveal pathnames like "/home/mseaborn/..." to the NaCl process.

That isn't ideal, although env vars are currently inherited by the NaCl process which expose similar information.  But it would be nice not to add to the set of things that are exposed this way.

Could you pass a hash of the filename to the NaCl process instead?

messages.author: Mark Seaborn
messages.text: Use C++-style casts?

messages.author: Mark Seaborn
messages.text:
From discussion in person:  10 is the number of requests that can be in progress at once.  If you have 11 requests in progress simultaneously, some can fail.  So this isn't a cache -- cache misses shouldn't affect correctness.

So you either need to fix that, or put in a big TODO and explanation here of the meaning of 10.  And don't call it "path_cache_". :-)

Why is this limit set so low when you're only mapping IDs -> filenames?  It's not like this is holding on to file descriptors.

messages.author: Mark Seaborn
messages.text:
I'm not sure 'nonce' is the appropriate term here, since it suggests the number is unguessable, that this is a cryptographic protocol, etc., which isn't the case.

Something like "file_token" instead, perhaps?
